Dear Centennial Community,

The Centennial Board of School Directors is pleased to announce that on Tuesday, July 28, 2020, the Board voted to approve Dr. Dana Bedden as the next Superintendent of Schools for the Centennial School District.

The Centennial Board of School Directors invites all community members to meet Dr. Bedden on Monday, August 3, 2020 at a virtual forum. The “Meet & Greet” forum will be moderated by Dr. Mark Hoffman, Executive Director of the Bucks County Intermediate Unit, from 7:00 p.m. until 8:00 p.m.

Input from residents is appreciated. Community members are invited to submit up to two (2) questions for Dr. Bedden through the following website:

Dear Centennial Community,

Beginning on Monday, June 22, we are adding an additional location to our breakfast and lunch distribution schedule on Mondays and Thursdays throughout the summer. The additional location is, The Glen at Bucks, 675 E. Street Road, Warminster from 10:40-11:10.

Here are all of the meal distribution locations and times:

· The Glen at Bucks - 10:40 – 11:10 a.m.

· Maple Street Park - 11:20 -11:50 a.m.

· McDonald Elem School - 11:30 a.m. - 1:00 p.m.

· Szymanek Park - 12:00 - 12:30 p.m.

· Crooked Billet - 12:40 - 1:10 p.m.

Sincerely,

Mrs. Shannon Stone

Supervisor of Food and Nutrition

post_text:
Dear Centennial Community;

We are accepting online registrations for incoming Kindergarten students for the 2020-21 school year. Students must be five years of age on or before August 31 to register for Kindergarten. In order to register a student, the following documents are required:

· A birth certificate

· Immunization records

· Four proofs of residency (acceptable list found at

https://www.centennialsd.org/Page/101

Once the online form is complete, the Registrar will be reaching out to families individually to complete their paperwork. For more information about the registration process, visit

https://www.centennialsd.org/Page/101

or email the Registrar at jennke@centennialsd.org

We encourage you to register as soon as possible so you can be informed of upcoming events and district news.

Sincerely,

Centennial School District Administration

Please consider helping Centennial School District’s Food Service program by donating to the emergency COVID-19 meal program.

One in seven children in the U.S. is fighting hunger. Because of COVID-19-related school closings, these students are even more at risk.

Thank you for your support.

post_text:
Tennent students qualified to NCFL Nationals

Dr. Mooney (Director of Speech and Debate) and Mr. Coughlin (Volunteer Coach) would like to recognize Nick Simila '20 and Ethan Baker '21 for their achievements this season in the Philadelphia Catholic Forensic League. The Philadelphia Catholic Forensic League draws competitors from Archdiocesan, private, public, and charter high schools in the Philadelphia area and surrounding suburbs. Nick and Ethan qualified to compete in the 2020 National Catholic Forensic League Grand National Tournament by placing in the top six in their events at the PCFL National Qualifier Tournament in February. Nick is a two-time qualifier to NCFL Nationals in Lincoln-Douglas Debate, and this would have been Ethan's first NCFL Nationals experience. We share their disappointment that we will not be traveling to Chicago this weekend due to the cancellation of NCFL Nationals, and we are very proud of all that Nick and Ethan have accomplished this season. Congratulations, Nick and Ethan!
text:

Dr. Mooney (Director of Speech and Debate) and Mr. Coughlin (Volunteer Coach) would like to recognize Nick Simila '20 and Ethan Baker '21 for their achievements this season in the Philadelphia Catholic Forensic League. The Philadelphia Catholic Forensic League draws competitors from Archdiocesan, private, public, and charter high schools in the Philadelphia area and surrounding suburbs. Nick and Ethan qualified to compete in the 2020 National Catholic Forensic League Grand National Tournament by placing in the top six in their events at the PCFL National Qualifier Tournament in February. Nick is a two-time qualifier to NCFL Nationals in Lincoln-Douglas Debate, and this would have been Ethan's first NCFL Nationals experience. We share their disappointment that we will not be traveling to Chicago this weekend due to the cancellation of NCFL Nationals, and we are very proud of all that Nick and Ethan have accomplished this season. Congratulations, Nick and Ethan!

On Tuesday May 12th, teachers and staff members from Centennial School District will be conducting a drive through of the Log College portion of the district to show support and appreciation for their students and the community. Hartsville Fire Company, Warminster Fire Department, and Ivyland Fire Company will be jointly participating in the event. The parade will be initiating from WTHS shortly after 330pm and driving through most of Warminster Township and Ivyland Borough.

Happy Teacher Week, to Mrs. Sweeney, Mrs. Jumper, Miss Thompson, and all the teacher assistants and the specials teachers. You all are excellent teachers and are being so helpful and wonderful during this dramatic school year. We are so grateful to be a part of the Davis community, thanks to the wonderful teachers. Thank you for everything, we appreciate all you have done.
The Farley family

I have been fortunate to be able to volunteer at McDonald Elementary school and in doing so, I get to see first hand how wonderful the McDonald teachers and staff are! They are truly Rock Stars! Seeing interactions between teacher and student, the love, the support, the teaching, the listening, the caring and sharing is heart-warming! I have a deep appreciation for the energy and excitement they bring to school and to learning! Thank you from the bottom of my heart for taking care of our kids, for teaching our kids, and for being such a strong positive influence on them!
Vicki

post_text: My son is in Mrs. Fazzio’s class and I’ve seen such an improvement in him since he went into her class. Academically, he is actually reading!!! He is sounding out words and remembering sight words, it’s a great feeling watching your child learn to read and I have Mrs. Fazzio and all the support staff at Willow Dale to thank :) I know with these times, it has to be very challenging for teachers and Mrs. Fazzio has been patient, kind, and very willing to help when the parents need it. She even hosts chats with the kindergarten class (which could turn into absolute chaos if not handled the right way), but they are organized and fun and each student gets to share. I’m glad my son has started his journey at Willow Dale with Mrs. Fazzio, she’s an amazing teacher and we’re lucky to have her as his teacher :)

post_text:
Hello CSD Parents and Community Members,

I am the president of the Centennial School Board. All of us on the board hope you and your families are staying safe and healthy during this difficult time.

I am writing to ask that if you have not done so already, to please take some time to fill out the superintendent search survey. Your input is invaluable to the board as we navigate through this process. After all, although we as the board are ultimately responsible for the smooth functioning of the district, it is your children who attend our schools, and therefore you have the most invested in the future of our district. Please take a moment to fill out the survey by clicking this link:
https://bciu.formstack.com/forms/go_bucksiu_org_centennialsurvey_community
Best,

Andrew Dixon

President, Centennial School Board

Your opinion is very important to the board, so please, take the survey!

Teacher Appreciation Week!
I'm writing this to my 5th grade math teacher Mrs.Fernandes.

I wanted to thank her for helping us through all of her work and helping us stay strong along the way. Even when things got hard online she still stayed strong and always gave us challenges so we would stay smart and healthy.
From,
Aiden E-K

Dear Mr. Bellinger,
Happy Teacher Appreciation week! Thank you for being such a cool teacher this whole year. I really like doing science in school and I am upset we didn’t get to finish what we started. You are doing a great job with online teaching and I love our zoom meetings each week. I am still learning new things each day even if we aren’t in the school building. I hope you are staying healthy and safe and I hope I can see you in person again soon. Enjoy this week being celebrated because you deserve it.

Love, Colin M

post_text:
Happy Teacher Appreciation Day to the special area teachers as McDonald Elementary School! Academics are important but you let our kids show a different side of themselves. They get the try out different gifts and talents in a safe, comfortable environment with you. They develop lasting relationships with you over their time at McDonald and see you year after year. On behalf of the Board of School Directors and Administration,

Today, May 6, is National School Nurse Day. It is certainly a very different day than we had hoped for but recognizing that only makes more tangible my sense of appreciation for the role our nurses play. The theme for this year is School Nurses: Supporting Students in Times of Crisis.

We would like to recognize our school nurses for their important role in helping our students not only on a daily basis but when we eventually reopen. Their skill, care and compassion for our students, staff and guests is remarkable, and, essential to our community's safety and well being.

Please join me in thanking them for their phenomenal work, commitment and kindness.

Warmly,

Dave
David E. Baugh, EdD
Superintendent of Schools
Centennial School District

Middle Bucks Institute of Technology
May 6 at 9:54 AM ·

“Madison Swallow is a sweet, respectful young woman who is thoughtful and considerate to her classmates and has a heart of gold. Her dedication to the field of cosmetology is evident with every client as she goes the extra mile to make sure they each feel special.

Although Madison excels in her haircolor techniques, her real passion is Skin Care and Makeup. Her determination and ambition to learn and conquer the newest techniques was the driving force that earned her a 2nd place in the SkillsUSA District 2 Esthetics Competition. She was one of the lead makeup artists for the SkillsUSA Halloween Fashion Show and is always there to volunteer her talent when the cosmetology class works with the local elementary and middle schools doing makeup for their plays.

Madison is currently employed in a salon and is planning to pursue her passion for a career as a stylist and makeup artist. With her sweet smile and caring personality adding to her talent, Madison is destined for success.”

JoAnn Mclaughlin
Cosmetology Teacher

#teamcsd

Teacher Appreciation Letter

Hi, My son is in special education classes at Tennent. His amazing teachers have been supporting him during this unusual time. Mr. Dan Hughes and Ms. Megan Lutz have been having daily office hours and weekly chats with the kids to keep everyone in the loop. It is great for my son to see his classmates every Friday on Zoom! They are always available for any questions we have with assignments. My son has been able to adapt along with their support.

His weekly speech sessions with Melanie Iuliano are looked forward to by my son.

We also appreciate all the hard work from the Nutrition staff and Ms. Stone arranging all the food deliveries to everyone!

Everyone has stepped up to work in these unusual times. We look forward to seeing all the staff in September!!!

Laura Murray

Centennial Food Service encourages those receiving meals at Maple Street Park, Szymanek Park, and Crooked Billet Park to bring their own cloth or reinforced bags/totes to help carry the meals as the plastic bags may tend to rip as you are walking home.

Breakfast and lunch distribution will continue to be every Monday and Thursday.

· Maple Street Park - 11:20 -11:50 a.m.

· McDonald Elementary School - 11:30 a.m. - 1:00 p.m.

· Szymanek Park - 12:00 - 12:30 p.m.

· Crooked Billet - 12:40 - 1:10 p.m.

Mrs. Shannon Stone

post_text: Junior Ethan Baker will be representing Tennent's Speech and Debate Team in the online Tournament of Champions this weekend. This tournament, sponsored by the University of Kentucky, features over 900 entries from 287 schools across eleven unique speech and debate events. Ethan will be competing in Oral Interpretation and Original Oratory. We are very proud of him for qualifying for this national tournament! Ethan has been working very hard throughout our school closure to prepare for the tournament, and we wish him the best of luck this weekend!

April 9, 2020

Dear Centennial Students, Staff, and Families,

Today, we received notification from Secretary of Education Pedro Rivera that all public schools will remain closed for the rest of the 2019-20 school year. Until we receive additional information and guidance from the Pennsylvania Department of Education, the Centennial School District will continue to provide its continuity of education plan, which will resume on Tuesday, April 14. The District will continue to provide meals for families in need as well.

Our thoughts are with all of the families in the Centennial School District in this difficult time. Stay safe and be well.

Sincerely,

The Centennial School District Administration

Centennial Education Association
April 3 at 10:04 AM ·

This year, 14 of William Tennent High School National Art Honor Society students chose to create portraits for refugee children in Malaysia and did an amazing job. These refugee children are facing hardships everyday, that we cannot even begin to imagine. Now, more than ever, the message that this project sends to children throughout the world is one of love, hope and connection.

Please take a few minutes to see the students, their artwork and the positive impact they are creating in the world. We all could use some more smiles right now.

Special thanks to Art Teacher Janna Francis for providing this opportunity and support to her students.

post_text:
Our School Nutrition Service department's first priority has always been the kids they serve. The school closure isn’t going to stop our dedicated staff from keeping our students well-nourished. Thank you to Ms. Shannon Stone,
Supervisor of Food and Nutrition (pictured below) and the entire Centennial School District Nutrition Services Team!

Beginning on Wednesday, March 18, our Food Service Department will be serving lunch and breakfast for the next day at various locations in the community. This service will be provided Monday - Friday.
The schedule will be as follows:
Maple Street Park - 11:20-11:50 a.m.
Szymanek Park - 12:00-12:30 p.m.
Crooked Billet - 12:40-1:10 p.m.
They will continue to serve breakfast from 8:00-9:00 a.m. and lunch from 12:00-1:00 p.m. Monday through Friday outside of McDonald Elementary School located at the front of the building.
All meals will be free to kids 18 and under.

post_text:
STEM K'Nex Challenge
Davis Elementary had a great time at the BCIU STEM Challenge. Both teams completed their projects within the two hour time limit. They did a wonderful job with their presentations to the judges.

While the students were waiting for the judges to decide on the winners, they enjoyed a lovely lunch. After lunch they announced the winners. Mitchell, Max and Ernie got nominated for Best Teamwork. Even though they did not win that category, we were proud of them for being nominated. All the students received a certificate for participating.

Out of the 64 teams competing, only one could be selected as winner to move on to the state competition. Our school did not have the winning team, but making it as far as the students did, they are definitely all winners!

William Tennent High School
March 9 at 8:59 AM ·

Our Jazz Ensemble traveled to Pennridge High School for their Jazz Festival this weekend. The ensemble was the only school to receive the highest rating of the night, Superior with Honors! Along with this, they received best saxophone section, best trumpet section, best trombone section, and best rhythm section! Jacob Broggi and Kevin Bergin also received soloist awards! Finally, the ensemble received the John McMordie Memorial Best Trumpet Section of the entire evening! The students were able to introduce themselves and speak to Mr. and Mrs. McMordie to learn more about their son, John.

Dear Centennial Community,

We are monitoring the situation in the Central Bucks School District. Central Bucks has posted a message to their community on their website which includes a FAQ from the CDC about the coronavirus. Centennial School District is continuing with the deep cleaning of the schools and the buses throughout the weekend. The District will continue with these precautionary measures until they are no longer needed.

We have received many questions from concerned parents. The District will be posting a FAQ on the website that will provide recommendations to parents and staff.

All official information from the District will be communicated through eAlerts, the district website, and district Facebook page.

Sincerely,
CSD Administration

Senator Robert "Tommy" Tomlinson
February 27 at 11:41 AM ·

Proud to announce the School Safety Grants totaling $813,415, were awarded to Bensalem Township School District, Bristol Borough School District Communications, Bristol Township School District, Centennial School District PA, Council Rock School District and Neshaminy School District. The grants were awarded by the School Safety and Security Committee within the Pennsylvania Commission on Crime and Delinquency (PCCD) as part of the School Safety and Security Grant Program. Eligible uses for the grants include hiring school security officers, purchasing security-related technology, completing safety and security assessments, implementing violence prevention curricula, offering counseling services for students, and creating other programs to protect students.

Dear Centennial Community;

We are now accepting registrations for incoming Kindergarten students for the 2020-21 school year. Students must be five years of age on or before August 31 to register for Kindergarten. In order to register a student, the following documents are required:

· A birth certificate

· Immunization records

post_text:
Congratulations to William Tennent students, Daulton Zeaman and Juliana Cave, for receiving the 2020 Prudential Spirit of Community Award (President's Volunteer Service Award).

The Prudential Spirit of Community Awards program is the United States’ largest youth recognition program based exclusively on volunteer community service.
Created in 1995 by Prudential and the National Association of Secondary School Principals (NASSP), the program honors middle level and high school students for outstanding service to others at the local, state and national level.

Thus far, it has recognized more than 130,000 young people who’ve made a difference – and inspired countless others to consider how they might contribute to their communities.

William Tennent High School
February 18 at 11:38 AM ·

The tradition continues…this year marks the 55th annual Black and White events at William Tennent High School! What started 55 years ago as one day in the gymnasium has exploded into a three-day, competition-laden extravaganza preceded by five weeks of planning and preparation. Divided alphabetically into two teams, Black (A - K) and White (L - Z), the participating students will face each other head-to-head in various challenges that will test their minds and bodies.

Our Academic Competition will be held on February 26 at 7:00 p.m. Doors will open at 6:15 p.m. No tickets are required for Academic Night, and family and friends are welcome to attend.

Pool Night is February 27 at 6:15 p.m. We will conclude the events with Gym Night on February 28 starting at 6:15pm. Both Pool & Gym Nights require tickets which can be purchased during all student lunches.

Should you have any questions, please contact our Black & White Night Advisors. bit.ly/2st72oB #BWAcademic #BWPool #BWGym

Exciting news! Klinger’s very own 8th grader, Devon DeCorte, has been selected for the US Club Soccer Under-14 National Team. This is an enormous honor. Only 18 boys from the entire nation are included in this selection. Centennial School District is proud to have an athlete-scholar performing at such a high level of competition.

The team will go on an international tour to Scotland and England in March. They will play games against the youth teams of four professional teams, and they will be provided with opportunities to learn about the two host nations that they will be visiting.

As part of the selection process for this U-14 National Team, Devon attended an identification camp at the Olympic Training Facility in Chula Vista, California in early December.

Here is the website if you want to learn more:
https://www.usclubsoccer.org/news_article/show/1086952

Unified Track & Field at William Tennent
The Special Olympics Unified Champion Schools program is aimed at promoting social inclusion through intentionally planned and implemented activities affecting systems-wide change. With sports as the foundation, the three-component model offers a unique combination of effective activities that equip young people with the tools and training to create sports, classrooms, and school climates of acceptance. These are school climates where students with disabilities feel welcome and are routinely included in, and feel a part of, all activities, opportunities and functions.

Here at William Tennent, we offer Unified Track during the PIAA Spring season. Next school year, we will also offer Unified Bocce in the PIAA Winter season.

Any students interested in being a partner or athlete for Unified Track this year can sign up in the Athletics Office or see Mr. Mulville (Room - C102).

post_text:
Spelling Bee:

Davis Elementary School held it’s Spelling Bee on Friday, February 7. The competition created exciting buzz around the building! We are proud of all of our students who participated; they were able to stand tall and show their spelling progress to faculty, students, and families in the audience. Our students worked hard to fly through parts of words, origins, definitions, and spelling rules to gain insight to those lists of words they were able to work through. It was a swarm of suspense as words like charactonym and poseur were posed to our students. Out of 41 original competitors, Shaun Dillon (winner) and Dillan Shafer (second place winner ) fluttered back and forth for a true word hive-off. The face-off lasted 14 rounds with Shaun taking the lead with the word stapes as the final challenge word.

shared_text:
Warminster Township
February 6 at 10:03 AM ·

STOP means STOP

Did you know it is illegal to pass a school bus when its red lights are flashing, and the stop arm is extended? In the state of Pennsylvania, if convicted of breaking this law, you could get a $250 fine, five points on your driving record, and a 60-day suspension of your license.

The Centennial School District bus drivers who observe this violation do prepare a written and signed report describing the incident. This statement is forwarded to local law enforcement to act upon. Many of our buses now come equipped with stop arm cameras. These cameras are automatically activated when the stop arm is extended and will record the violating vehicle's license. The recording is shared with local law enforcement.

Remember, it is illegal to pass a school bus when its red lights are flashing and the stop arm is extended. Stop means stop.

post_text: #LoveTheBusMonth
shared_text:
National School Transportation Association
February 4 at 10:44 AM ·

Motorists risk children’s lives when they fail to stop for the school bus as it loads and unloads its passengers. Yet it’s estimated that over 10 million drivers illegally pass school buses every year. To keep children safe, start by learning the laws in your state.

It’s illegal to pass a school bus within the roadway as it drops off or picks up passengers—regardless of the direction of approach. Remember that there is no “safe” way to illegally pass the school bus, so be cautious when sharing the road with it. Finally, let others know that putting kids’ lives at risk is not OK. Report aggressive drivers and spread the word by sharing material found at www.schoolbusfacts.com. Take a pledge to brake for the school bus! #brakeforthebus #lovethebus #schoolbussafety #schoolbus

Dear Centennial Community;

We are now accepting registrations for incoming Kindergarten students for the 2020-21 school year. Students must be five years of age on or before August 31 to register for Kindergarten. In order to register a student, the following documents are required:

· A birth certificate

· Immunization records

· Four proofs of residency (acceptable list found at http://www.centennialsd.org/Page/101)

Parents/guardians can register a student online or in-person. For more information about the registration process, visit http://www.centennialsd.org/Page/101 or call the Registrar at 215-441-6000, Ext. 11046.

We encourage you to register as soon as possible so you can be informed of upcoming events and district news.

Community Flyer:
March 7, 2020 AAUW Lansdale Branch in conjunction with Montgomery County Community College is conducting a STEM event for girls only.

“Discover Your Future” strives to overturn the stereotype that girls are less capable, or not interested in Science, Technology, Engineering, and Math. This is a day of interactive workshops is lead by outstanding women leaders and role models in industry and academia.

The program geared to girls grades 5 to 8th creates a fun environment to excite girls with opportunities in STEM. The program on March 7, 2020 will run from 8:30 in the morning to 3:30 in the afternoon at Montgomery County Community College's Blue Bell Campus for a nominal charge. Scholarships available.

Registration Closes February 29th.

Register Online at: https://dyf2020.eventbrite.com

(eventbrite charges a processing fee)

OR Complete the form and mail $10. to the address listed.

Additional forms and information: https://aauwlansdale.org/dyf

We hope to attract not only girls who have an interest in STEM, and those girls who have little opportunity or interest now.

shared_text:
Middle Bucks Institute of Technology
January 22 at 4:22 PM ·

The state of Pennsylvania has six new PA Emissions Inspectors certified and ready to conduct emissions testing. These Automotive Technology students completed the PENNSYLVANIA ENHANCED EMISSION INSPECTION CERTIFICATION course, which provides the theory of state-wide emission inspection procedures and tests required for the PA Enhanced Emissions Inspection Certification. This training is mandated by Penn DOT for all inspectors and automotive repair technicians conducting emission inspections. Congratulations to Ben Salvador – CBE, Jason Schwarz – Upper Bucks Christian School,
Dan Gindhart – CB South, Pearson Kerrigan- CB West, Zack Varano – William Tennent, and Aleczander Watson – CB South (from left to right). #cbsschools #teamcsd #cbsdproud

The Southampton Community Band would like to invite you to the second concert of their 22nd season, “Animal Farm.“ The concert will consist of classic band and orchestra literature, and popular and Broadway favorites all about animals!

The concert is this Saturday, January 18, 8 PM at Klinger Middle School. Doors open at 7:30 and individual tickets are available at the door for $10/$15. Season subscriptions are also available. The band is directed by Willow Dale music teacher, Mr. Regosch.

Visit www.southamptonband.org or https://www.facebook.com/Southampton-Community-Band-304012733131/ for additional information.

William Tennent High School
January 10 at 12:53 PM ·

The time is approaching for students to begin selecting courses for the 2020–21 school year. You and your child can review our Panther Pathways Program of Studies in order to learn about available courses and options for next year. Over the next few weeks, your child will be recommended for courses by our teachers and will have the opportunity to choose elective classes.

For more information, please be sure to attend our Course Selection Night on January 16 from 6:00 p.m. – 8:00 p.m. in the William Tennent High School auditorium. Parents of current grades 6 and 7 students are also welcome to attend to learn about the exciting opportunities William Tennent High School can provide their children in the near future!

Should you have any questions regarding course selection, please reach out to your child’s counselor for further information. #chooseyourpath

https://sites.google.com/centennialsd.org/panther-pathways/program-of-studies

post_text:
Retired Davis Elementary teacher pens magical tale of friendship, family and adventure for globally-minded kids. Watson and Jason Move to Australia by Nancy Avery is now available on Amazon!

Nancy's inspiration to become an author came from her own classroom. "While I was teaching geography, I wanted a creative way to hook my student's interest, and thus the tale of Watson and Jason began," she says. Her own beagle became the story's central character, and her nieces and nephews were also a part of the story. "My goal is to write a series of children's books following Watson and Jason as they visit all seven continents."

Myth - Centennial School District is trying to make money renting the stadium to Archbishop Wood instead of using it for William Tennent High School football games. The District has an agreement with Archbishop Wood that includes waiving fees on the use of the stadium.

post_text:
Dear Centennial Community,
We need your help to educate high school students on basic budgeting and money management skills. TruMark Financial in conjunction with William Tennent High School will hold a REAL Solutions Financial Reality Fair at William Tennent High School on Thursday, October 24, from 8:30 a.m. to 1:30 p.m.

Two hundred high school students will participate in a hands-on simulation. Budgeting skills will be learned by making financial decisions acting as independent adults. This event is supported by over 30 community volunteers who will provide financial counseling and guide the students through the budgeting process. To volunteer for the event, please contact Dr. Albert Catarro, cataal@centennialsd.org , 215-441-6181, Ext. 11479. Volunteers will attend a pre-event information session at 8:15 a.m. at William Tennent High School.

Thank you in advance for your support and consideration!

post_text:
William Tennent High School – TruMark Financial Credit Union
Financial Reality Fair.

Call for volunteers for the day. We need your help to make this financial literacy event happen.

TruMark Financial in conjunction with William Tennent High School will hold a REAL Solutions Financial Reality Fair at William Tennent High School, Warminster, on Thursday, October 24, 2019, 8:30 a.m. to 1:30 p.m. Financial literacy and budgeting skills are the focus of the day

Two hundred high school students will participate in a hands-on simulation. Budgeting skills will be learned by making financial decisions acting as independent adults. This event is supported by over 30 community volunteers who provided financial counseling and guided the students through the budgeting process. To volunteer for the event please contact Dr. Albert Catarro, cataal@centennialsd.org or 215 - 441 - 6181 ext. 11479. Volunteers will attend a pre-event information session at 8:15 am at William Tennent High School.

post_text:
Dear Centennial Community;

The state of Pennsylvania offers a Children's Health Insurance Program (CHIP), which covers uninsured children and teens up to age 19 - and no family earns too much to qualify.

CHIP provides quality, comprehensive health insurance for routine doctor visits, prescriptions, dental, eye care, eyeglasses, mental health, and much more. CHIP covers uninsured kids who are not eligible for Medical Assistance. For most families, CHIP is free - for others, it is low cost.

For more information please see the attached flyer or visit the CHIP website at www.chipcoverspakids.com.

post_text: The Centennial School District is working closely with Upper Southampton Township Police Department in the investigation. As a reminder to the community, please call 911 if you see something that doesn't seem right. We work in close collaboration with all three township police departments and take all reports seriously.
shared_text:
Upper Southampton Township Police Department
September 5, 2019 at 7:51 AM ·

Yesterday USPD investigated the report of a suspicious middle-aged female who was operating a maroon minivan that had briefly stopped at a bus stop at approx. 0825 hours and told several juveniles “The bus has already come and you missed the bus.” The female then drove away and did not engage the juveniles in any more conversation.

The Department is continuing to investigate this incident in collaboration with the Centennial School District PA and has preliminarily determined that there was no luring threat or danger whatsoever to the juveniles. As normal practice, USPD will have officers patrolling the bus stops to help ensure the safety of the children of our community.

USPD appreciates our communities involvement in being the extra “eyes and ears” but we would ask if you do observe an incident such as this, please call 9-1-1 immediately so that a police response and investigation is not delayed. #community

post_text: Due to the facility issues at William Tennent, this week's summer school exams will be held at McDonald Elementary School in Room B-8. The timing of the exams will remain the same (Monday 9-11 a.m. and Tuesday 1-3 p.m.). Be sure to bring your username and password to the testing session in order to log into your program. Additionally, please check in at the main office for directions to the computer lab when arriving at the school. Thank you for your understanding and flexibility.
